Angell,<br><br>
I was in the US Air Force in Danang in 1970-71.  Within our unit, there was not much problem with race at all.  But I did see a couple of incidents, which I'll describe. <br>
__________ <br><br>
November 5, 1970--Diary Entry<br>
Flew again this morning for 4 hours. Flew up to Hue and the DMZ, on an oritntation flight for 2 new pilots. At the DMZ we flew alert orbit for approximately one hour. The pilots really had their assess hanging because we weren't SAR equipped and configured. Later, off Danang, we fired all the rounds to the miniguns. For the first time I shot the #3 (the ramp gun). Previously, I had shot only the #1 gun (on the left side of the aircraft).<br>
'Went to the show tonight at the main compound. Coming back the truck was full. It stopped in front of two Negros, who wanted a ride. No one got out. Then it went another 20 yards, and half the load wanted out. The two guys weren't picked up. What could I say?<br>
___________<br><br>
I had a situation develop which was very uncomfortable for me.  It was a gathering of black airmen outside a barracks, where a lot of people were listening to someone speak.  Since I had to walk through this area on the sidewalk, I was not comfortable.  I remember taking my Gerber folding knife out of its sheath and keeping it in my hand as I walked through.  Nobody bothered me, and the situation passed.  In hindsight I'm not sure there was an incident, only that the conditions made me uncomfortable.  <br><br>
I hope this helps.  These are the only two situations I can remember.  People who were directly involved in missions didn't care a wit about where a person came from, or what he looked like, only that he could do the job (there were no &quot;she's,&quot; so what I say here is &quot;politically correct&quot;).<br><br>

